"L E S S O N Fraction-Decimal-Percent Equivalents Power Up Building Power facts Power Up J mental math a. Calculation: 7 × $35.00 b. Decimals: 12.75 ÷ 10 c. Equivalent Fractions: 6 4  9 n d. Exponents: 102 e. Estimation: 6 1 6  3 4 f. Fractional Parts: 3 8 of 80 g. Statistics: Find the range of the set of numbers: 89, 99, 29, 89. h. Calculation: 10 × 8, + 1, 2 , + 2, × 4, − 2, ÷ 6, × 9, + 1, 2 , ÷ 2, ÷ 2, ÷ 2 problem solving The teacher asked for two or three volunteers. Adam, Blanca, Chad and Danielle raised their hands. From these four students, how many possible combinations of two students could the teacher select? How many different combinations of three students could the teacher select? New Concept Increasing Knowledge We may describe part of a whole using a fraction, a decimal, or a percent. A of the circle is shaded. 0.5 of the circle is shaded. 50% of the circle is shaded. Thinking Skill Identify What property allows us to rename a fraction by multiplying by a form of 1? Recall that when we rename a fraction, we multiply by a form of 1 such as 2 2, 5, or 100 100. Another form of 1 is 100%, so to convert a fraction or a decimal to a percent, we multiply the number by 100%. Connect Explain how we know that 100% is a form of 1. Example 1 Write 7 10 as a percent. Solution To change a number to its percent equivalent, we multiply the number by 100%. 10  100%  700% = 70% Saxon Math Course 2"
"Example 2 Write 2 3 as a percent. Solution We multiply by 100 percent. 3  100%  200%  66 2 3% Notice the mixed-number form of the percent. Example 3 Write 0.8 as a percent. Solution We multiply 0.8 by 100%. 0.8 × 100% = 80% Example 4 Complete the table. Solution For a and b we find decimal and percent equivalents of 1 3. a. 3 1.00 0.3 b. 1 3  100%  100%  33 1 3% For c and d we find a fraction (or a mixed number) and a percent equivalent to 1.5. c. 1.5 = 1 5 10  1 1 d. 1.5 × 100% = 150% For e and f we find fraction and decimal equivalents of 60%. e. 60% = 60 100  3 f. 60% = 60 100 = 0.6 For g and h, the whole number 2 is shown as the fraction 2 1. g. 2 h. 2 × 100% = 200% Fraction Decimal Percent a. b. c. 1.5 d. e. f. 60% g. h."
"Practice Set Connect Complete the table. Written Practice Strengthening Concepts * 1. (46) Bicyclist Mario Cipollini pedaled one stage of the 1999 Tour de France in about 3.9 hours. If he traveled about 195 kilometers, what was his average speed in kilometers per hour? 2. (24) Write the prime factorization of 1008 and 1323. Then reduce 1008 1323. 3. (12) In 1803 the United States purchased the Louisiana Territory from France for $15 million. In 1867 the United States purchased Alaska from Russia for $7.2 million. The purchase of Alaska occurred how many years after the purchase of the Louisiana Territory? * 4. (36, 43) Analyze Red and blue marbles were in the bag. Five twelfths of the marbles were red. a. What fraction of the marbles were blue? b. What was the ratio of red marbles to blue marbles? c. Analyze If one marble is taken from the bag, what is the probability of taking a red marble? Write the probability as a fraction and as a decimal number rounded to two places. * 5. (46) A 9-ounce can of peaches sells for $1.26. Find the unit price. 6. (28) The average of two numbers is the number halfway between the two numbers. What number is halfway between two thousand, five hundred fifty and two thousand, nine hundred? 7. (22) Diagram this statement. Then answer the questions that follow. Van has read five eighths of the 336-page novel. a. How many pages has Van read? b. How many more pages does he have to read? * 8. (9) Analyze Copy this figure on your paper. Find the length of the unmarked sides, and find the perimeter of the polygon. Dimensions are in centimeters. All angles are right angles. Fraction Decimal Percent a. b. c. 1.1 d. e. f. 4% g. h. Saxon Math Course 2"
