"19. (67) Name each three-dimensional figure: a. b. c. 20. (60) Compare: 2 3 of 96 6 of 84 21. (52) Analyze Find ab − (a − b) if a = 5 6 and b = 3 Analyze For problems 22–24, solve and check each equation. Show each step. * 22. (Inv. 7) w = 15 * 23. (Inv. 7) b − 1.6 = (0.4)2 * 24. (Inv. 7) 20w = 5.6 Simplify: 25. (49) 2 yd 1 ft 7 in.  1 yd 2 ft 8 in. 26. (50) 0.5 m  100 cm 1 m  10 mm 1 cm 27. (26) 12 1 2  4 1 5  2 2 28. (26) 7 1 2  a6 2 3  1 1 5b * 29. (68) Generalize Simplify. a. (−8) + (−7) − (−15) b. (−15) + (+11) − | +24 | c. a 1 3b  a2 3b 30. (26, 43) Find the product of 2.25 and 1 1 3. Early Finishers Math Applications Look at the three figures in problem 19 above. a. What plane shape is formed if you make a vertical cut to divide each figure in half? Sketch the plane shape. b. What plane shape is formed if you make a horizontal cut? Sketch the plane shape."
"Fractional Part of a Number, Part 2 Power Up Building Power facts Power Up N mental math a. Positive/Negative: (−8) − (−12) b. Exponents: 45 × 10−3 c. Algebra: 7w + 1 = 50 d. Estimate/Percent: Estimate 15% tip on a $19.81 bill. e. Measurement: 400 m to km f. Percent: 80% of $25 g. Primes/Composites: What is the prime factorization of 50? h. Calculation: 10% of 80, × 2, 2 , × 7, − 1, ÷ 3, 2 , × 12, 2 , ÷ 6 problem solving In a class of 20 boys, 14 wear brown shoes, 12 wear watches, 11 are on a soccer team, and 10 are tall. How many tall, soccer-playing boys who wear watches and brown shoes could be in the class? New Concept Increasing Knowledge In some fractional-part-of-a-number problems, the fraction is unknown. In other fractional-part-of-a-number problems, the total is unknown. As discussed in Lesson 60, we can translate these problems into equations by replacing the word “of ” with a multiplication sign and the word “is” with an equal sign. Example 1 What fraction of 56 is 42? Solution We translate this statement directly into an equation by replacing “what fraction” with WF , “of ” with a multiplication symbol, and “is” with an equal sign. What fraction of 56 is 42? question WF × 56 = 42 equation L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 2"
"Thinking Skill Explain Why do we divide both sides of the equation by 56? To solve, we divide both sides by 56. WF  56  42 56 divided by 56 WF  3 4 simplified If the question had been “What decimal part of 56 is 42?” the procedure would have been the same, but as the last step we would have written 3 4 as the decimal number 0.75. WD = 0.75 Discuss How do we change a fraction to an equivalent decimal? Example 2 Three fourths of what number is 60? Solution In this problem the total is the unknown. But we can still translate directly from the question to an equation. Three fourths of what number is 60? question × WN = 60 equation To solve, we multiply both sides by 4 3. 3  3 4  WN  60  4 3 multiplied by 4 WN = 80 simplified Had the question been phrased using 0.75 instead of 4 3, the procedure would have been similar. Seventy-five hundredths of what number is 60? question 0.75 × WN = 60 equation To solve, we can divide both sides by 0.75. 0.75  WN 0.75  60 0.75 divided by 0.75 WN = 80 simplified Practice Set Formulate Translate each statement into an equation and solve: a. What fraction of 130 is 80? b. Seventy-five is what decimal part of 300? c. Eighty is 0.4 of what number? d. Sixty is 5 6 of what number? e. Sixty is what fraction of 90?"
"f. What decimal part of 80 is 60? g. Forty is 0.08 of what number? h. Six fifths of what number is 60? i. For which of the above problems were you given the fractional part and asked to find the total or whole? Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (55) Miguel is reading the book Call of the Wild, by Jack London. During the first 3 days of the week he read an average of 15 pages per day. During the next 2 days, Miguel averaged 25 pages per day. For all five days, what was the average number of pages Miguel read per day? 2. (46) Twelve ounces of Brand X costs $1.14. Sixteen ounces of Brand Y costs $1.28. Brand X costs how much more per ounce than Brand Y? 3. (50) Use a unit multiplier to convert 4 1 2 feet to inches. 4. (66) Ira counted the number of car and food commercials during a one hour television program. The ratio was 2 to 3. If 18 of the commercials were for food, how many commercials did Ira count altogether? * 5. (72) Model Use a ratio box to solve this problem. If 5 pounds of apples cost $4.25, how much would 8 pounds of apples cost? 6. (22, 36) Diagram this statement. Then answer the questions that follow. Five sixths of the 300 triathletes completed the course. a. How many triathletes completed the course? b. What was the ratio of triathletes who completed the course to those who did not complete the course? Formulate Write equations to solve problems 7−11. * 7. (74) Fifteen is 3 8 of what number? * 8. (74) Seventy is what decimal part of 200? * 9. (74) Two fifths of what number is 120? 10. (60) The store made a 60% profit on the $180 selling price of the coat. What was the store’s profit? 11. (60) The shoe salesperson received a 20% commission on the sale of a $35 pair of shoes. What was the salesperson’s commission? * 12. (67, 70) a. What is the volume of this cube? b. What is its surface area? Math Language A unit multiplier is a ratio equal to 1 that is composed of two equivalent measures. 3 in. Saxon Math Course 2"
