"L E S S O N Complex Fractions Power Up Building Power facts Power Up P mental math a. Positive/Negative: (+6) + (−18) b. Decimals/Exponents: 6.25 × 10−2 c. Algebra: 9 a − 4 = 32 d. Fractional Parts: 12 is 2 3 of what number? e. Measurement: 5 mm to cm f. Fractional Parts: What is 2 3 of 12? g. Statistics: Find the average of the set of numbers: 95, 95, 50. h. Calculation: What is the total cost of a $25 video game plus 6% sales tax? problem solving The squares of the first nine counting numbers are each less than 100. Altogether, how many counting numbers have squares that are less than 1000? New Concept Increasing Knowledge A complex fraction is a fraction that contains one or more fractions in the numerator or denominator. Each of the following is a complex fraction: a b b c One way to simplify a complex fraction, is to multiply the complex fraction by a fraction name for 1 that makes the denominator 1. Example 1 Simplify: Solution We focus our attention on the denominator of the complex fraction. Our goal is to make the denominator 1. We multiply the denominator by the reciprocal of 3, which is 3 2, so that the new denominator is 1. We also multiply the numerator by 3 2. Thinking Skill Analyze What is the relationship between fraction pairs such as 3 and 3 2? What is their product?"
"  or 9 We multiplied the complex fraction by a complex name for 1 to change the denominator to 1. Since 9 10 divided by 1 is 9 10, the complex fraction simplifies to 9 10. An alternative method for simplifying some complex fractions is to treat the fraction as a division problem. We can change the format of the division problem to a more familiar form. divided divisor 5  2 Then we simplify the division using the method described in Lesson 25. 5  2 3  3 5  3 2  9 Example 2 Simplify: Solution First we write both numerator and denominator as fractions. Now we multiply the numerator and the denominator by 1 100.   or Example 3 Simplify: 15 Solution We begin by writing both numerator and denominator as improper fractions. Saxon Math Course 2 Visit www. SaxonPublishers. com/ActivitiesC2 for a graphing calculator activity."
"Now we multiply the numerator and the denominator by 3 22.   1 or 2 1 Discuss Why do you think 3 22 was selected as the multiplier in this example? Example 4 Change 83 1 3% to a fraction and simplify: Solution Thinking Skill Generalize Name three complex fractions equal to 1. A percent is a fraction that has a denominator of 100. Thus 831 3% is 83 1 Next we write both numerator and denominator as fractions. Now we multiply the numerator and the denominator by 1 100.    5 Practice Set Generalize Simplify each complex fraction: a. 37 1 b. 12 c. 2 Change each percent to a fraction and simplify: d. 66 2 3% e. 8 1 3% f. 4 1 6% g. Justify Which two properties of multiplication do we use to simplify complex fractions? Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (46) a. Nestor finished a 42-kilometer bicycle race in 1 hour 45 minutes (13 hr). What was his average speed in kilometers per hour? b. Explain How did we know that 1 hour and 45 minutes is 13 hours? 2. (28) Akemi’s scores in the diving competition were 7.9, 8.3, 8.1, 7.8, 8.4, 8.1, and 8.2. The highest and lowest scores were not counted. What was the average of the remaining scores? 3. (66) Use a ratio box to solve this problem. The school art club is having an exhibit. The ratio of oil paintings to acrylic paintings being displayed is 2 to 5. If there are 35 paintings displayed, how many of them are oil paintings?"
