"17. (48) Complete the table. Fraction Decimal Percent a. b. c. d. 0.1% * 18. (75) Analyze A square sheet of paper with an area of 81 in.2 has a corner cut off, forming a pentagon as shown. a. What is the perimeter of the pentagon? b. What is the area of the pentagon? c. Explain How did you find the area of the pentagon? * 19. (Inv. 6) Conclude What type of parallelogram has four congruent angles but not necessarily four congruent sides? 20. (12, 28) When water increases in temperature from its freezing point to its boiling point, the reading on a thermometer increases from 0°C to 100°C and from 32°F to 212°F. The temperature halfway between 0°C and 100°C is 50°C. What temperature is halfway between 32°F and 212°F? Justify For problems 21–24, solve and check each equation. Show each step. * 21. (Inv. 7) x − 25 = 96 * 22. (Inv.7) 3 m  12 * 23. (Inv. 7) 2.5p = 6.25 * 24. (Inv. 7) 10 = f  3 1 Simplify: 25. (20) 2132  52 26. (16) 1 ton − 400 lb 27. (26, 43) 3 3 4  4 1 6  10.422 (fraction answer) 28. (35, 43) 3 1 8  6.7  8 1 4 (decimal answer) * 29. (68) Generalize a. (−3) + (−5) − (−3) − | +5 | b. (−2.4) − (+1.2) * 30. (76) Estimate Before dividing, determine whether the quotient is greater than or less than 1 and state why. Then perform the calculation."
"L E S S O N Percent of a Number, Part 2 Power Up Building Power facts Power Up P mental math a. Positive/Negative: (+12) − (−18) b. Exponents: 4 × 106 c. Ratio: 100 150  30 a d. Estimation: Estimate 15% of $61. e. Measurement: 25 cm to m f. Fractional Parts: 12 is 3 4 of n . g. Statistics: Find the average of the set of numbers: 100, 60, 90, 70. h. Calculation: 10% of 50, × 6, + 2, ÷ 4, × 2, 1 , × 9, 1 , × 7, ÷ 2 problem solving On a balanced scale are a 25-g mass, a 100-g mass, and five identical blocks marked x, which are distributed as shown. What is the mass of each block marked x? Write an equation illustrated by this balanced scale. New Concept Increasing Knowledge In Lesson 74 we practiced fractional-part problems involving fractions and decimals. In this lesson we will practice similar problems involving percents. First we translate the problem into an equation; then we solve the equation. Example 1 What percent of 40 is 25? Solution We translate the question to an equation and solve. What percent of 40 is 25? question Wp × 40 = 25 equation To solve we divide both sides of the equation by 40. WP  40  25 40 divided by 40 WP  5 8 simplified X X X X 25-g X 100-g Saxon Math Course 2"
"Since the question asked “what percent” and not “what fraction,” we convert the fraction 5 8 to a percent. 8  100%  62 1 2% converted to a percent Thinking Skills Summarize What steps did we follow to convert 5 to a percent? Verify How can you decide if this answer is reasonable? Example 2 What percent of $3.50 is $0.28? Solution We translate and solve. What percent of $3.50 is $0.28? question Wp × $3.50 = $0.28 equation WP  $3. $3.  $0.28 $3.50 divided by $3.50 WP  0.28 3.5 simplified We perform the decimal division. WP  0.28 3.5  2.8 35  0.08 divided Thinking Skills Summarize How did we convert 0.08 to 8%? This is a decimal answer. The question asked for a percent answer so we convert the decimal 0.08 to 8%. WP = 8% converted to a percent Example 3 Seventy-five percent of what number is 600? Solution We translate the question to an equation and solve. We can translate 75% to a fraction or to a decimal. We choose a fraction for this example. Seventy-five percent of what number is 600? question × WN = 600 equation To solve, we multiply both sides by 100 over 75 as follows:  75 10  WN  600  100 75 multiplied by 100 WN = 800 simplified"
"Example 4 Fifty is what percent of 40? Solution Since 50 is more than 40, the answer will be greater than 100%. We translate to an equation and solve. Fifty is what percent of 40? question 50 = WP × 40 equation We divide both sides by 40. 40  WP  40 divided by 40 4  WP simplified We convert 5 4 to a percent. WP  5 4  100%  125% converted to a percent Example 5 Sixty is 150 percent of what number? Solution Predict Do you think the answer will be greater than or less than 60? Why? We translate by writing 150% as either a decimal or a fraction. We will use the decimal form here. Sixty is 150% of what number? question 60 = 1.5 × WN equation We divide both sides of the equation by 1.5. 1.5  1. 5  WN 1. divided by 40 40 = WN simplified Practice Set Generalize Find each percent or quantity in a–f. a. Twenty-four is what percent of 40? b. What percent of 6 is 2? c. Fifteen percent of what number is 45? Saxon Math Course 2"
"d. What percent of 4 is 6? e. Twenty-four is 120% of what number? f. What percent of $5.00 is $0.35? g. Rework example 5, writing 150% as a fraction instead of as a decimal. h. Justify How can you show that your answer to problem f is correct? Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (65) Use a ratio box to solve this problem. Tammy saved nickels and pennies in a jar. The ratio of nickels to pennies was 2 to 5. If there were 70 nickels in the jar, how many coins were there in all? Refer to the line graph below to answer problems 2– 4. Test Number Jeremy’s Test Scores Score (% Correct) 2. (38, 60) If there were 50 questions on Test 1, how many questions did Jeremy answer correctly? 3. (28, 38) What was Jeremy’s average score? (What was the mean of the scores?) 4. (38, Inv. 5) a. Which score did Jeremy make most often? (What was the mode of the scores?) b. What was the difference between his highest score and his lowest score? (What was the range of the scores?) 5. (67) Name the shape of each object: a. a marble b. a length of pipe c. a box of tissues * 6. (72) Model Use a Case 1/Case 2 ratio box to solve this problem. One hundred inches equals 254 centimeters. How many centimeters equals 250 inches?"
"* 7. (36, 71) Model Diagram this statement. Then answer the questions that follow. Three fifths of those present agreed, but the remaining 12 disagreed. a. What fraction of those present disagreed? b. How many were present? c. How many of those present agreed? d. What was the ratio of those who agreed to those who disagreed? e. If there were 50 people present and 30 people agreed, would the ratio of those who agreed to those who disagreed change? Why or why not? Formulate Write equations to solve problems 8–11. * 8. (74) Forty is 4 25 of what number? 9. (60) Twenty-four percent of 10,000 is what number? * 10. (77) Twelve percent of what number is 240? * 11. (77) Twenty is what percent of 25? * 12. (73) Simplify: a. 25(−5) b. −15(−5) c. 250 5 d. 225 13. (48) Complete the table. 14. (46) A pair of pants costs $21 plus 7.5% sales tax. What is the total cost of the pants? Summarize how you found your answer. * 15. (76) Generalize Simplify: a. 14 2 b. 60 * 16. (75) Analyze Find the area of this symmetrical figure. Dimensions are in feet. Corners that look square are square. 17. (67, 70) Draw a cube with edges 2 cm long. a. What is the volume of the cube? b. Describe how to find the surface area of a cube. Fraction Decimal Percent a. 0.2 b. c. d. 2% Saxon Math Course 2"
