"L E S S O N Estimating Square Roots Irrational Numbers Power Up Building Power facts Power Up U mental math a. Positive/Negative: (−1.5) − (−7.5) b. Order of Operations/Exponents: (5 × 10−5)(5 × 10−5) c. Algebra: 100 = 5w − 20 d. Measurement: Convert −20°C to degrees Fahrenheit. e. Calculation: 20 × 3 3 f. Percent: 33 1 3% less than $24 g. Geometry: Which shape(s) has no vertices? h. Calculation: 25% of 44, × 3, − 1, ÷ 4, × 7, − 1, ÷ 5, × 9, + 1, 1 , − 1, 1 problem solving The figure represents a three-dimensional solid. Draw the top, front, back, left, and right views of the solid. New Concepts Increasing Knowledge estimating square roots These counting numbers are perfect squares: 1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, . . . Reading Math Read 225 as “the square root of 25.” Recall that the square root of a perfect square is an integer. 225  5 236  6 The square root of a number that is between two perfect squares is not an integer but can be estimated. 229 = ? Since 29 is between the perfect squares 25 and 36, we can conclude that 229 is between 225 and 236. 225  5 229 = ? 236  6"
"Saxon Math Course 2 We see that 229 is between 5 and 6. On this number line we see that 229 is between 5 and 6 but not exactly halfway between. Example 1 Between which two consecutive whole numbers is 2200? Solution We remember that 2100 is 10, so 2200 is more than 10. We might guess that 2200 is 20. We check our guess. 20 × 20 = 400 too large Our guess is much too large. Next we guess 15. 15 × 15 = 225 too large Since 15 is still too large, we try 14. 14 × 14 = 196 too small We see that 14 is less than 2200 and 15 is more than 2200. So 2200 is between the consecutive whole numbers 14 and 15. Generalize Using the same method, we find that 210 is between which two consecutive whole numbers? irrational numbers At the beginning of this lesson we found that 229 is between 5 and 6. We can refine our estimate by finding a decimal (or fraction) that is closer to 229. We try 5.4. 5.4 × 5.4 = 29.16 too large Since 5.4 is too large, we try 5.3. 5.3 × 5.3 = 28.09 too small We see that 229 is between 5.3 and 5.4. We may continue refining our estimate by finding numbers closer to 229. However, no matter how many numbers we try, we will not find a decimal (or fraction) that equals 229. If we use a calculator, we can quickly find a number close to 229. If we enter these keystrokes or (depending on the type of calculator) the number displayed on an 8-digit calculator is 5.3851648 Thinking Skill Explain How many decimal places will be in the product of these two factors? How do you know? This number is close to 229 but does not equal 229, as we see in the first step of checking the answer: 5.385164  5.3851648 Visit www. SaxonPublishers. com/ActivitiesC2 for a graphing calculator activity."
"We see immediately that the product is not 29.00000000000000 because the digit in the last decimal place is 4. Actually 229 is a number that cannot be exactly expressed as a decimal or fraction and therefore is not a rational number. Rather 229 is an irrational number —a number that cannot be expressed as a ratio of two integers. Nevertheless, 229 is a number that has an exact value. For instance, if the legs of this right triangle are exactly 2 cm and 5 cm, we find by the Pythagorean theorem that the length of the hypotenuse is 229 cm. 2 cm 5 cm 29 cm If we measure the hypotenuse with a centimeter ruler, we find that the length is about 5.4 cm, which is an approximation of 229 cm. Other examples of irrational numbers include π (the circumference of a circle with a diameter of 1), 22 (the length of the diagonal of a square with sides of 1), and the square roots of counting numbers that are not perfect squares. The irrational numbers, together with the rational numbers, make up the set of real numbers. Real Numbers Rational Irrational Numbers Numbers All of the numbers represented by points on the number line are real numbers and are either rational or irrational. Example 2 Draw a number line and show the approximate location of the points representing the following real numbers. Then describe each number as rational or irrational. 𝛑 22 2.3 1 Solution We draw a number line and mark the location of the integers from −1 through 4. We position π (≈ 3.14) between 3 and 4 but closer to 3. Since 22 is between 21 (= 1) and 24 (= 2), we position 22 between 1 and 2 but closer to 1. The repeating decimal 2.3 1 2 1 32 is closer to 2 than to 3. The negative fraction 1 2 is halfway between 0 and −1. –1 2.3 π – Repeating decimal numbers are rational. Thus, both 1 2 and 2.3 are rational, while 22 and 𝛑 are irrational."
