"L E S S O N Semicircles, Arcs, and Sectors Power Up Building Power facts Power Up V mental math a. Positive/Negative: (−0.25) − (−0.75) b. Scientific Notation: (5 × 105)2 c. Algebra: 80 = 4m − 20 d. Measurement: Convert 1 sq. yd to sq. ft. e. Percent: 200% 0f $25 f. Percent: 200% more than $25 g. Geometry: A yard is shaped like an octagon and each side measures 4 ft. What is the perimeter of the yard? h. Rate: At 12 mph, how far can Sherry skate in 45 minutes? problem solving If three standard number cubes are tossed simultaneously, what is the probability that the sum of the three number cubes will be less than or equal to 5? New Concept Increasing Knowledge A semicircle is half of a circle. Thus the length of a semicircle is half the circumference of a circle with the same radius. The area enclosed by a semicircle and its diameter is half the area of the full circle. Example 1 Find the perimeter of this figure. Dimensions are in meters. Solution The length of the semicircle is half the circumference of a circle whose diameter is 10. Length of semicircle  pd ≈ 13.142110 m2 ≈ 15.7 m L E S S O N Saxon Math Course 2"
Now we can label all the dimensions on the figure and add them to find the perimeter. Thinking Skill Analyze How do we know that the height of the rectangle is 10 meters? Perimeter ≈ 10 m + 4 m + 15.7 m + 4 m ≈ 33.7 m Example 2 Find the area of this figure. Dimensions are in meters. Solution We divide the figure into two parts. Then we find the area of each part. A 1 = pr 2 A 2 = l × w  3.14125 m22 = 4 m × 10 m ≈ 39.25 m2 = 40 m2 The total area of the figure equals A 1 + A 2. Total area = A 1 + A 2 ≈ 39.25 m2 + 40 m2 ≈ 79.25 m2 Math Language A sector is a portion of a circle bound by two radii and an arc. We can calculate the lengths of arcs and the areas of sectors by determining the fraction of a circle represented by the arc or sector. Example 3 Find the area of the shaded sector of this circle. 15.7 300° 6 cm A1 A2
"Solution The central angle of the shaded sector measures 60º (the full circle, 360º, minus the given angle, 300º). Since 60º is 1 6 of a circle 1 60 360  1 62, the area of the sector is 1 6 of the area of the circle. Area of 60º sector = pr 2  3.1416 cm2 16 cm2 ≈ 18.84 cm2 As we discussed in Investigation 2, an arc is part of the circumference of a circle. In the following figure we see two arcs between point A and point B. A B C The arc from A clockwise to B is called a minor arc because it is less than a semicircle. We may refer to this arc as arc AB (abbreviated AB ) ). The arc from A counterclockwise to B is called a major arc because it is greater than a semicircle. Major arcs are named with three letters. The major arc between point A and point B may be named arc ACB. Analyze Name all the minor arcs found in the figure above. Then name all the major arcs. We can measure an arc in degrees. The number of degrees in an arc equals the measure of the central angle of the arc. If minor arc AB in the figure above measures 120º, then the measure of major arc ACB is 240º because the sum of the measures of the major arc and minor arc must be 360º. Example 4 In this figure, central angle AOC measures 70º. What is the measure of major arc ADC? Solution An arc may be described by the measure of its central angle. The arc in the interior of the 70º angle AOC is a 70º arc. However, the larger arc from point A counterclockwise through point D to point C measures 360º minus 70º, which is 290º. A C O D Saxon Math Course 2"
"Example 5 A minor arc with a radius of 2, centered at the origin, is drawn from the positive x-axis to the positive y-axis. What is the length of the arc? Solution A minor arc is less than 180º. We see that the arc is 1 4 of a circle, which is 90º. The length of the arc is 1 4 of the circumference of a circle with a radius of 2 (and a diameter of 4). Length of 90º arc  pd  3.1414 units2 ≈ 3.14 units Practice Set Analyze Find each measure of this figure. Dimensions are in centimeters. (Use 3.14 for π.) a. perimeter b. area c. Explain Describe how to find the area of this 45° sector. (Leave π as π.) Then find the area. d. Find the perimeter of the figure in problem c. (Include the arc and two segments. Use 3.14 for π.) Written Practice Strengthening Concepts 1. (60) The merchant sold the item for $12.50. If 40 percent of the selling price was profit, how much money did the merchant earn in profit? * 2. (94) Analyze If two marbles are pulled from a bag containing eight blue marbles, seven green marbles, and six yellow marbles, what is the probability that both marbles will be green? Express the probability as a decimal number. 3. (55) In 10 jump-rope trials, Kiesha’s average number of jumps per minute is 88. If her least number of jumps, 70, is not counted, what is her average for the remaining 9 trials? 4. (46) The 36-ounce container cost $3.42. The 3-pound container cost $3.84. The smaller container cost how much more per ounce than the larger container? 45° 4 cm x y –2 –2 –1"
